  "notes": "Fula / Fulah / Fulfulde / Pular / Peul. Atlantic-Congo (Senegambian branch) language spoken across the Sahel from Senegal to Sudan by ~65 million people. Major language of Guinea-Bissau (Fula/Pular), Senegal, Guinea, Mali, Nigeria (Fulfulde). KEY FEATURES: (1) VOWEL LENGTH: contrastive; aa/ee/ii/oo/uu vs a/e/i/o/u — phonemic in all dialects. (2) IMPLOSIVES: ɓ=[ɓ], ɗ=[ɗ], ƴ=[ʄ] are phonemic in many dialects; represent a Niger-Congo substrate feature. (3) FRICATIVE ALLOPHONES: bh=[β] and dh=[ð] are intervocalic allophones/contrasts of /b/ and /d/ in some dialects. (4) CONSONANT MUTATION (LENITION): stop → fricative in intervocalic contexts — a core morphophonological process. (5) PRENASALIZED STOPS: mb/nd/ng/nj. (6) GEMINATE CONSONANTS: contrast with singletons in some dialects. (7) DIALECTS: Pular (Guinea), Fulfulde (Nigeria/Cameroon), Pulaar (Senegal) differ in lexicon and phonology; this file models standard/common features.",
